-- Sample Chapters for Days 1-3

-- Day 1: From Stage Star to Silent Struggles (Foundation)
INSERT INTO chapters (day_number, title, subtitle, content, task_description, before_questions, after_questions) VALUES (
  1,
  'From Stage Star to Silent Struggles',
  'Building Your Inner Self',
  E'# From Stage Star to Silent Struggles\n\n## THE MOMENT EVERYTHING CHANGED\n\nTom stood in the auditorium doorway, phone glowing, thumb scrolling through TikTok. Applause for another speaker leaked through the doors—a sound he used to live for, now just background noise.\n\n"Tom Hammond? Is Tom here tonight?"\n\nHis mom grabbed his arm. "Tom! They''re calling you!"\n\nHe shrugged her off. "Just one more video."\n\nBy the time his dad grabbed the phone, the organizers had moved on. Tom, fourteen, had just missed his slot at regionals—the same competition where he''d won first place eighteen months ago.\n\nHis mom''s face: pure disappointment.\n\n## THE RISE\n\nRewind three years. Tom was different.\n\nAt eleven, this sixth-grader could hold 200 people captive with just his voice. While friends ground Fortnite after school, Tom practiced speeches for two hours in front of his mirror.\n\nBy seventh grade, Tom was that kid—the one who MCed assemblies, the one everyone''s parents wanted at gatherings. After winning regionals at twelve, his debate coach said: "You''re going to do something big someday."\n\nTom believed him.\n\n## WHAT ACTUALLY HAPPENED\n\nHere''s what nobody tells you: what happened to Tom is happening to everyone your age. And it''s not your fault.\n\nDr. Anna Lembke (legit psychiatrist) wrote Dopamine Nation explaining how TikTok, Instagram, and YouTube hijack your brain. Every scroll gives you dopamine—the same chemical released when you eat your favorite food or get a text from your crush.\n\nStanford tracked 2,500 teenagers for three years. Those spending 3+ hours daily on entertainment apps showed a 60% drop in passion activities. Brain scans revealed reduced activity in the prefrontal cortex—the part handling delayed gratification.\n\nTom''s brain: Stage performances released dopamine naturally, but required work. TikTok? Instant dopamine every 15 seconds.\n\nReality check: Average teenager gets 237 notifications daily. Takes just 66 days to rewire neural pathways.\n\nYou''re not weak. You''re being gamed by billion-dollar algorithms. The game is rigged.\n\nBut you can still win.\n\n## THE SPARK FRAMEWORK\n\nTom used a system called SPARK—five steps that actually work:\n\n### S - SURFACE the Pattern\n\nTom tracked phone usage for one week: 6.5 hours daily. That''s 195 hours monthly on his phone vs. 2 hours practicing. "Almost 200 hours scrolling. Two hours on what I care about. That''s not who I want to be."\n\n**YOUR TURN:** Settings → Screen Time (iPhone) or Digital Wellbeing (Android). Look at your daily average. Don''t judge. Just look.\n\n### P - PINPOINT the Why\n\nTom''s dad asked: "Why''d you stop caring about speaking?"\n\nAfter silence: "What if I''m not actually that good? What if I disappoint everyone? At least on my phone, I don''t have to find out."\n\nThe phone was escape from performance anxiety.\n\n**YOUR TURN:** "When I reach for my phone, I''m usually avoiding feeling..."\n\n### A - ANCHOR to Identity\n\nStanford research: Identity-based motivation is 3x more effective than goals.\n\nTom wrote: "I am a storyteller who makes people feel less alone."\n\nNot "I want to be." "I AM."\n\nStuck it on his mirror. Read it every morning. Sounds corny. Worked.\n\n**YOUR TURN:** "I am a [identity] who [impact]." Write it somewhere visible.\n\n### R - REBUILD with Micro-Commitments\n\nTom started with five minutes, three times that week. That''s it.\n\n- Week 1: 5 minutes, 3 days\n- Week 2: 10 minutes, 4 days\n- Week 3: Watch open mic (don''t perform)\n- Week 4: One story at family dinner\n\nStanford found "tiny habits" are 400% more likely to stick than big goals.\n\n**Day 23—He Almost Quit:**\n\nTerrible day. Failed math test. Fight with his best friend.\n\nCame home exhausted.\n\nPhone right there. Just one video.\n\nUnlocked it. YouTube loaded. Finger hovering.\n\nThen—his lock screen. Photo of himself at eleven, mid-speech, lit up.\n\nHe closed YouTube. Voice-recorded a story about his day.\n\nAdded link #24 to his paper chain.\n\nAlmost relapsing ≠ relapsing.\n\n**YOUR TURN:** Pick ONE thing. 5-10 minutes max. Three times this week.\n\n### K - KINDLE Community\n\nTom reconnected with debate team. Asked his cousin Alex to be his accountability partner. Started attending open mics. Being around people who cared reminded his brain why this mattered.\n\n**YOUR TURN:** Text ONE person right now. Tell them what you''re working on. Ask for weekly check-ins.\n\n## THE TECHNIQUES\n\n### #1: Substitution Game\n\nTom''s three moves when reaching for his phone:\n\n1. Read one page from a great speech (pocket copy)\n2. Do 20 push-ups (disrupts mental loops)\n3. Voice-memo a story idea\n\nKey: Easier than unlocking his phone.\n\n**YOUR TURN:** Pick three easy alternatives. Write them in notes app now.\n\n### #2: The "Later" Technique\n\nNot "I won''t watch TikTok." Instead: "I can watch after dinner, but right now I''m choosing to practice."\n\nBrain doesn''t feel deprived with "later."\n\n### #3: Change Your Environment\n\nTom''s phone charged in the kitchen overnight. Speech notes where phone used to sit. Trophies on his desk.\n\nEnvironmental changes reduce bad habits 80% without willpower.\n\n**YOUR TURN:** Tonight—charge phone outside your bedroom.\n\n### #4: Visual Progress\n\nTom made a paper chain. Every 10-minute practice = one link.\n\nBy day 30, it wrapped his room. Physical proof: "I''m someone who shows up."\n\n**YOUR TURN:** Paper chain, calendar X''s, marble jar—make progress visible.\n\n## THE COMEBACK\n\nSix months later, same competition. Same venue.\n\nTom walked on stage, phone forgotten in his pocket.\n\n"I want to tell you about the day I chose a screen over my dreams, and what happened when I chose my dreams back."\n\nSeven minutes of truth. The shame. The hollow hours. The fear. The small daily choices.\n\nThree seconds of silence. Then applause.\n\nSecond place. But more importantly—proof he could come back.\n\nTom today at sixteen: Volunteers as peer mentor. Chain hit 247 links. Placed third at states.\n\n"My phone''s a tool now, not my personality. I use it. It doesn''t use me."\n\nThree months later, fourteen-year-old Layla found him: "That chain thing—did it work?"\n\nTom showed her everything. That night he realized: his recovery gave him new purpose.\n\nThe student became the teacher.\n\n## YOUR MOMENT\n\nTom''s story isn''t about superhuman willpower. It''s about one Tuesday when he decided who he''d been wasn''t who he wanted to become.\n\nSome of you will bookmark this and come back when ready. That''s fine.\n\nBut if you''re feeling that pull right now—that voice saying "maybe I could actually do this"—don''t ignore it.\n\nPick ONE thing:\n- Write your identity statement in phone notes\n- Text one person for weekly check-ins\n- Delete one app that takes more than it gives\n\nNot all three. Just one.\n\nThe rest of this book will be here.\n\nBut if you''re ready now? Move. Don''t let this feeling fade.\n\nIn six months, you''ll either wish you''d started today, or you''ll be glad you did.\n\nYour call.',
  'Write your identity statement: "I am a [identity] who [impact]." Then choose ONE action:\n\n1. Share your identity statement with someone you trust\n2. Text someone to be your accountability partner\n3. Delete one distracting app from your phone\n\nComplete your chosen action and document it in a text note (what you did, how it felt, what you learned).',
  '[
    {"id": "q1", "question": "How often I grab phone when working", "scale": "1=rarely, 7=constantly"},
    {"id": "q2", "question": "Remember yesterday''s scrolling", "scale": "1=yes, 7=barely"},
    {"id": "q3", "question": "Feel after phone session", "scale": "1=energized, 7=empty"},
    {"id": "q4", "question": "Time on passion this year", "scale": "1=more, 7=abandoned"},
    {"id": "q5", "question": "Time before phone urge", "scale": "1=30+ min, 7=under 5"},
    {"id": "q6", "question": "Use phone to avoid feelings", "scale": "1=rarely, 7=always"},
    {"id": "q7", "question": "Phone vanished 24hrs", "scale": "1=relieved, 7=panicked"}
  ]'::jsonb,
  '[
    {"id": "q1", "question": "After reading this chapter, how aware are you of your phone usage patterns?"},
    {"id": "q2", "question": "How clear is your identity statement to you now?"},
    {"id": "q3", "question": "How committed do you feel to the action you chose?"},
    {"id": "q4", "question": "How hopeful are you about making positive changes?"},
    {"id": "q5", "question": "How ready do you feel to continue with the next 29 days?"}
  ]'::jsonb
);

-- Day 2: Active Listening
INSERT INTO chapters (day_number, title, subtitle, content, task_description, before_questions, after_questions) VALUES (
  2,
  'Active Listening',
  'The art of truly hearing others',
  E'# Active Listening\n\n## More Than Just Hearing\n\nListening is not the same as hearing. Hearing is passive—it happens automatically. Listening is active—it requires intention, focus, and practice.\n\n## The Three Levels of Listening\n\n### Level 1: Internal Listening\nYou''re hearing the words, but your mind is on your own thoughts, judgments, or what you''ll say next. We all do this, but it''s the least effective form of listening.\n\n### Level 2: Focused Listening\nYou''re fully present with the other person, paying attention to their words, tone, and body language. This is where real communication begins.\n\n### Level 3: Global Listening\nYou''re not only focused on the person, but also aware of what''s NOT being said—the emotions, the energy, the subtle cues. This is listening mastery.\n\n## Why Active Listening Matters\n\nWhen you truly listen to someone:\n- They feel valued and understood\n- You gain deeper insights\n- Trust is built naturally\n- Conflicts are resolved more easily\n- Relationships strengthen\n\n## The Active Listening Technique\n\n1. **Give full attention**: Put away distractions\n2. **Show you''re listening**: Use body language and small verbal cues\n3. **Provide feedback**: Paraphrase to confirm understanding\n4. **Defer judgment**: Listen to understand, not to respond\n5. **Respond appropriately**: Be honest, candid, and respectful\n\n## Today''s Practice\n\nHave a conversation with someone—a family member, friend, or classmate. Practice Level 2 or Level 3 listening. Really focus on understanding their perspective without thinking about your response.\n\nAfterward, write a summary of what they shared and what you learned.',
  'Have a conversation with someone (minimum 5 minutes). Practice active listening by giving them your full attention. Then write a text summary (150-300 words) of what they shared, what you learned, and one insight about their perspective that you might have missed with casual listening.',
  '[
    {"id": "q1", "question": "How often do you find your mind wandering during conversations?"},
    {"id": "q2", "question": "How well do you understand others'' perspectives in conversations?"},
    {"id": "q3", "question": "How present and focused are you when someone is speaking to you?"}
  ]'::jsonb,
  '[
    {"id": "q1", "question": "How focused were you during this conversation?"},
    {"id": "q2", "question": "How much deeper was your understanding compared to typical conversations?"},
    {"id": "q3", "question": "How likely are you to practice active listening in future conversations?"}
  ]'::jsonb
);

-- Day 3: Body Language Basics
INSERT INTO chapters (day_number, title, subtitle, content, task_description, before_questions, after_questions) VALUES (
  3,
  'Body Language Basics',
  'Communicating without words',
  E'# Body Language Basics\n\n## The Silent Language\n\nResearch suggests that up to 93% of communication is nonverbal. That means your body language often speaks louder than your words.\n\n## The Key Elements of Confident Body Language\n\n### 1. Posture\n**Poor posture**: Slouching, hunched shoulders, looking down\n- Communicates: Insecurity, low energy, disinterest\n\n**Confident posture**: Shoulders back, spine straight, head up\n- Communicates: Confidence, alertness, respect\n\n### 2. Eye Contact\n**Too little**: Looking away, at the floor, at your phone\n- Communicates: Dishonesty, disinterest, anxiety\n\n**Just right**: Comfortable, natural eye contact (50-70% of the time)\n- Communicates: Confidence, honesty, engagement\n\n**Too much**: Staring without breaking\n- Communicates: Aggression, intensity, discomfort\n\n### 3. Gestures\n**Closed gestures**: Arms crossed, hands in pockets, minimal movement\n- Communicates: Defensiveness, discomfort, closed-mindedness\n\n**Open gestures**: Natural hand movements, arms relaxed, welcoming stance\n- Communicates: Openness, enthusiasm, confidence\n\n### 4. Facial Expressions\nYour face is the most expressive part of your body. A genuine smile, raised eyebrows when listening, and a relaxed expression all contribute to positive communication.\n\n## The Power Pose Effect\n\nStudies show that holding a confident posture for just 2 minutes can:\n- Increase testosterone (confidence hormone)\n- Decrease cortisol (stress hormone)\n- Make you feel more confident and powerful\n\n## Cultural Awareness\n\nRemember: Body language can vary across cultures. What''s confident in one culture might be disrespectful in another. Always be observant and adapt accordingly.\n\n## Today''s Practice\n\nYou''ll practice and photograph confident body language. Focus on:\n- Standing or sitting tall\n- Shoulders back and relaxed\n- Open, welcoming posture\n- Natural, confident facial expression',
  'Take a photo of yourself demonstrating confident body language. Stand or sit with good posture, shoulders back, and an open stance. You can be in a casual setting, but focus on conveying confidence through your body position. Upload the photo.',
  '[
    {"id": "q1", "question": "How aware are you of your body language in daily interactions?"},
    {"id": "q2", "question": "How confident does your typical posture make you feel?"},
    {"id": "q3", "question": "How much do you think your body language affects how others perceive you?"}
  ]'::jsonb,
  '[
    {"id": "q1", "question": "How much more aware of your body language are you now?"},
    {"id": "q2", "question": "How confident did you feel holding a strong posture?"},
    {"id": "q3", "question": "How likely are you to consciously improve your body language going forward?"}
  ]'::jsonb
);
